In <strnlghtCq0E4H.JD6@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:

>In article <2rcs7j$3ad@sunforest.mantis.co.uk>,
>mathew <mathew@mantis.co.uk> wrote:
>>
>>I don't care if server operators cause hassle for US citizens, but I'm
>>not going to put up with being treated as some sort of criminal.

>You don't understand the situation. It isn't you they are treating like a
>criminal. They are protecting themselves. In the U.S. their lawyers have
>told them that 2.3 infringes. There is a tort called contributory
>infringement, and if they accept 2.3 keys on their key server they can be
>sued for that. That some 2.3 keys (from the U.S., let's say) are the product
>of an infringement, and others (yours, say) aren't is not a distinction they
>are going to be able to make and remain clean. This is, after all, an MIT
>site, not some private or amateur operation, and they have to be scrupulous
>in their behavior.

Sternlight is probably correct here.  (I feel a need to say this because,
IMHO, it happens so rarely, and it should be encouraged.)

